The Herald reader Denise Cornish’s picture of her 29-month-old grandson, Levi Richards, eagerly scanning the newspaperPicture: Supplied
Little Levi, my grandson, simply loves his daily read.
Every Monday at my home he takes out the Weekend Post and that day’s The Herald.
Last Saturday the Weekend Post featured an article about London.
As he is crazy about castles, he was delighted to see Big Ben and other buildings, just the castles he was looking for.
Train them young and they will never be bored.
I just love the versatility of our paper.
Littlies can learn numeral and letter identification.
My grandson loves to call out the number of each page and there are the colour photographs where each one tells its own story.
A picture of an adult feeding a penguin the other day enabled us to together explore the sea and its animal kingdom.
To his great delight he learnt that a penguin eats fish, walks on the sand and swims in the water.


For older children, there is so much on offer as there is good material for school projects, which means the paper has shelf life.
I save interesting historical articles, such as the one in Weekend Post, of places of interest in our country, for future use.
Children are never too young to read, and the double whammy is parents and grandparents discover new things at the same time.
-D Cornish, Walmer, Port Elizabeth


